-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Nov 18
-- 
-- Tue Nov 18, 2014 03:07AM EST
-- None



SOFIA, Nov 18 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- The finance ministry has started talks over fresh borrowing on international markets to finance increased spending under the 2014 state budget revision (Presa, Monitor, Capital daily, 24 Chasa). -- The Sofia City Court scheduled the insolvency case of Corporate Commercial Bank [6C9.BB] for November 24. The hearing will be held behind closed doors (Standart, Trud, Capital daily, Monitor, 24 Chasa, Duma). -- Deeper and more enhanced integration of Bulgaria into NATO and the EU and rearmament of the Bulgarian army with weapons meeting the NATO standards are among the defence ministry's top priorities, Defence Ministrer Nikolay Nenchev said after meeting U.S. Ambassador to Bulgaria Marcie Ries (Standart, Sega, Duma). -- Accession to the Schengen area is an achievable target for Bulgaria and Romania, Deputy Prime Minister Meglena Kuneva said after meeting Romania's Ambassador to Bulgaria Anton Pacuretu (24 Chasa, Presa, Sega). PRESA - Bulgaria is highly likely to lose EU funds of 100 million euros($124.87 million)  in the sphere of healthcare as the deadline for wrapping up public procurement procedures by December 10 is too short, Health Minister Petar Moskov said (Presa, . CAPITAL DAILY - Mandatory voting could be introduced in Bulgaria as early as 2015, ruling centre-right GERB party's Deputy Chairman Tsvetan Tsvetanov said.  -- Bulgaria is losing an estimated 500 million levs a year from illegal trading in archaeological artifacts due to inconsistent legislation, local non-government organisation Forum Association said (Monitor, Sega).